www.thepeerage.com/p10164.htm#i101634 |title=Ralph de Neville, 1st Earl of Westmorland |page=10164 \u00a7101634 |publisher=thePeerage.com |accessdate=March 2014}}\n*{{cite book |last=Harriss |first=Gerald |year=2006 |title=Shaping the Nation: England 1360\u20131461 |publisher=Oxford University Press }}\n*{{cite book |last=Neville |first=Cynthia J. |year=1998 |title=Violence, Custom and the Law |publisher=Edinburgh University Press }}\n*{{cite book |last=Swallow |first=Henry J. |year=1885 |title=De Nova Villa: or, The House of Nevill in Sunshine and Shade |location=Newcastle upon Tyne |publisher=Andrew Reid }}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.luminarium.org/encyclopedia/ralphneville.htm ''Luminarium Encyclopedia: Sir Ralph Neville, 1st Earl of Westmorland (1364\u20131425)'']\n*[http://www.luminarium.org/encyclopedia/houseofneville.htm ''Luminarium Encyclopedia; War of the Roses: House of Neville]\n*[http://www.luminarium.org/encyclopedia/ralphneville1effigy.jpg ''Engraving of Ralph Neville, Earl of Westmorland's effigy'']\n* {{Cite web |url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p1450.htm#i14497 |title=Person Page |website=thepeerage.com |accessdate=4 October 2017 }}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Earl Marshal]] | before=[[Thomas Holland, 1st Duke of Surrey|The Duke of Surrey]] | after=[[John Mowbray, 2nd Duke of Norfolk|The Duke of Norfolk]] | years=1400\u20131412}}\n{{s-reg|en}}\n{{s-new|creation}}\n{{s-ttl| title  = [[Earl of Westmorland]]\n       | years  = 1397\u20131425 }}\n{{s-aft| rows   = 2 | after  = [[Ralph Neville, 2nd Earl of Westmorland|Ralph Neville]] }}\n{{s-bef| before = [[John Neville, 3rd Baron Neville de Raby|John Neville]] }}\n{{s-ttl| title  = [[Baron Neville de Raby]]\n       | years  = 1388\u20131425 }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Westmorland, Ralph Neville, 1st Earl Of}}\n[[Category:1360s births]]\n[[Category:1425 deaths]]\n[[Category:14th-century English nobility]]\n[[Category:15th-century English nobility]]\n[[Category:People from County Durham]]\n[[Category:Neville family]]\n[[Category:Earls Marshal]]\n[[Category:Knights of the Garter]]\n[[Category:Male Shakespearean characters]]\n[[Category:Earls of Westmorland]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|14th/15th-century English nobleman}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox noble\n| name         = Ralph Neville\n| title        = 1st [[Earl of Westmorland]]<br>4th [[Baron Neville de Raby]]{{efn|The [[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]] uses a different numbering system and numbers him the 6th Baron Neville and his father the 5th etc. {{harv|Tuck|2008}}.}}\n| image        = Ralph Neville.jpg\n| caption      = Effigy at [[Staindrop]] Church\n| alt          = \n| spouse       = [[Margaret de Stafford|Margaret Stafford]] ({{abbr|d.|died}} {{abbr|1396|9 June 1396}})<br>[[Joan Beaufort, Countess of Westmorland|Joan Beaufort]] ({{abbr|m.|married}} 1396)\n| issue        = {{plainlist}}\n*'' '''With Margaret Stafford''' ''\n* [[John Neville (d. 1420)|John, Lord Neville]]\n* [[Philippa de Neville|Philippa, Baroness Dacre]]\n*'' '''With Joan Beaufort''' ''\n* [[Eleanor Neville, Countess of Northumberland|Eleanor, Countess of Northumberland]]\n* [[Katherine Neville, Duchess of Norfolk|Katherine, Duchess of Norfolk]]\n* [[Richard Neville, 5th Earl of Salisbury|Richard, 5th Earl of Salisbury]]\n* [[Robert Neville (bishop)|Robert, Bishop of Salisbury]]\n* [[William Neville, Earl of Kent|William, Earl of Kent]]\n* [[George Neville, 1st Baron Latimer|George, 1st Baron Latimer]]\n* [[Edward Neville, 3rd Baron Bergavenny|Edward, 3rd Baron Bergavenny]]\n* [[Anne Stafford, Duchess of Buckingham|Anne, Duchess of Buckingham]]\n* [[Cecily Neville, Duchess of York|Cecily, Duchess of York]]\n{{endplainlist}}\n| issue-link   = #Marriages and issue\n| issue-pipe   = more...\n| titles       = \n| noble family = [[House of Neville]]\n| house-type   = Dynasty\n| father       = [[John Neville, 3rd Baron Neville de Raby|John, 3rd Baron Neville de Raby]]\n| mother       = Maud Percy\n| birth_date   = c. 1364\n| birth_place  = \n| death_date   = 21 October 1425 (aged c. 61)\n| death_place  = \n| burial_date  = 1425\n| burial_place = [[Staindrop]] Church, [[County Durham]]\n| occupation   = \n}}[[File:Coat of arms of Sir Ralph Neville, 1st Earl of Westmorland, KG.png|thumb|243px|Coat of arms of Ralph Neville, 1st Earl of Westmorland: ''Gules, a [[saltire]] argent'']]\n\n'''Ralph Neville, 1st Earl of Westmorland''' {{postnominals|country=GBR|KG|PC}} <small>[[Earl Marshal]]</small> (c. 1364{{snd}}21 October 1425), was an English nobleman of the [[House of Neville]].\n\n==Family==\nRalph Neville was born about 1364, the son of [[John Neville, 3rd Baron Neville de Raby]], and Maud Percy (d. before 18 February 1379), daughter of [[Henry de Percy, 2nd Baron Percy]] of [[Alnwick]], Northumberland, by Idoine de Clifford, daughter of [[Robert de Clifford, 1st Baron de Clifford]].{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=552}} Neville had a younger brother, and five sisters:<ref>{{Harvnb|Cokayne|1936|p=503}}; {{Harvnb|Richardson III|2011|pp=244\u20136}}.</ref>\n\n*Thomas Neville, 5th Baron Furnivall, who married Joan Furnival. Father of [[Maud Neville, 6th Baroness Furnivall]], wife of [[John Talbot, 1st Earl of Shrewsbury|John Talbot, 7th Baron Talbot]].\n*Lady Alice Neville, who married William Deincourt, 3rd Lord Deincourt\n*Lady Maud Neville, who married Sir William le Scrope<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p1450.htm#i14498|title=Person Page|website=thepeerage.com|access-date=2017-10-04}}</ref>\n*Lady Idoine Neville\n*Lady Eleanor Neville, who married [[Ralph Lumley, 1st Baron Lumley]].\n*Lady Elizabeth Neville, who became a nun.\n\nNeville's father married secondly, before 9 October 1381, Elizabeth Latimer (died 5 November 1395), daughter of [[William Latimer, 4th Baron Latimer]]. By his father's second marriage Neville had a brother and sister of the half blood:<ref>{{Harvnb|Cokayne|1936|p=503}}; {{Harvnb|Richardson III|2011|pp=242\u20136}}.</ref>\n\n*John Neville, 6th Baron Latimer (c. 1382{{snd}}10 December 1430), who married firstly, Maud Clifford (died c. 26 August 1446), daughter of [[Thomas de Clifford, 6th Baron de Clifford|Thomas Clifford, 6th Baron Clifford]], whom he divorced before 1413-17, and by whom he had no issue. She married secondly, [[Richard of Conisburgh, 3rd Earl of Cambridge]], beheaded 5 August 1415 for his part in the [[Southampton Plot]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Richardson IV|2011|pp=400\u20131}}.</ref>\n*Lady Elizabeth Neville, who married Sir Thomas Willoughby.\n\n==Career==\nNeville's first military service was in [[Brittany]] under [[Richard II of England|King Richard II's]] uncle, [[Thomas of Woodstock, 1st Duke of Gloucester|Thomas of Woodstock]], who knighted him at [[Saint-Omer]] in July 1380. On 14 November 1381 he and his cousin, [[Henry Percy (Hotspur)|Henry \"Hotspur\" Percy]], were commissioned to preside over a duel between an Englishman and a Scot, and on 1 December 1383 he and his father were commissioned to receive from the Scots 24,000 marks for the ransom of [[David II of Scotland|King David]]. On 26 October 1385 he was appointed joint [[Governor of Carlisle]] with [[Thomas de Clifford, 6th Baron de Clifford|Sir Thomas Clifford]], and on 27 March 1386 was appointed, together with Clifford, joint [[Lord Warden of the Marches|Warden]] of the [[Scottish Marches|West March]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Cokayne|1959|p=544}}; {{Harvnb|Tait|1894|p=275}}; {{Harvnb|Richardson I|2011|p=506}}.</ref>\n\nNeville inherited the title at the age of 24 after his father's death on 17 October 1388, and was summoned to Parliament from 6 December 1389 to 30 November 1396 by writs directed to ''Radulpho de Nevyll de Raby''. On 25 October 1388 he was appointed, with others, to survey the fortifications on the Scottish border, and on 24 May 1389 was made keeper for life of the royal forests north of the [[River Trent|Trent]]. In 1393 and 1394 he was employed in peace negotiations with Scotland.<ref>{{Harvnb|Cokayne|1959|p=545}}; {{Harvnb|Tait|1894|p=275}}; {{Harvnb|Richardson III|2011|p=246}}.</ref>\n\nIn 1397 Neville supported King Richard's proceedings against Thomas of Woodstock and the [[Lords Appellant]], and by way of reward was created [[Earl of Westmorland]] on 29 September of that year.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=552}} However his loyalty to the King was tested shortly thereafter. His first wife, Margaret Stafford, had died on 9 June 1396, and Neville's second marriage to Joan Beaufort before 29 November 1396 made him the son-in-law of King Richard's uncle, [[John of Gaunt, 1st Duke of Lancaster]]. Thus, when King Richard banished John of Gaunt's eldest son and heir, Henry Bolingbroke, on 16 September 1398, and confiscated Bolingbroke's estates after John of Gaunt's death on 3 February 1399, Westmorland was moved to support his brother-in-law.  Bolingbroke landed with a small force at [[Ravenspur]] in July 1399. Westmorland and the [[Henry Percy, 1st Earl of Northumberland|Earl of Northumberland]] were in the deputation at the [[Tower of London|Tower]] which received King Richard's abdication, and Westmorland bore the small sceptre called the \"virge\" at Bolingbroke's coronation as [[Henry IV of England|King Henry IV]] on 13 October 1399.<ref>{{Harvnb|Cokayne|1959|pp=545\u20136}}; {{Harvnb|Tait|1894|p=276}}; {{Harvnb|Richardson III|2011|p=246}}; {{Harvnb|Tuck|2009}}.</ref>\n\nFor his support of the new King, Westmorland was rewarded with a lifetime appointment as [[Earl Marshal]] on 30 September 1399 (although he resigned the office in 1412), a lifetime grant of the [[Honour of Richmond|honour]] of [[Richmond, North Yorkshire|Richmond]] on 20 October (although the grant was not accompanied by a grant of the title [[Earl of Richmond]]), and several wardships.<ref name=\"Cokayne 1959 546\">{{Harvnb|Cokayne|1959|p=546}}; {{Harvnb|Tait|1894|p=276}}; {{Harvnb|Tuck|2009}}.</ref> Before 4 December he was appointed to the King's council.  In March 1401, Westmorland was one of the commissioners who conducted negotiations for a marriage between the King's eldest daughter, [[Blanche of England]], and [[Louis III, Elector Palatine|Louis]], son of [[Rupert, King of Germany|Rupert, King of the Romans]], and in 1403 was made a [[Knight of the Garter]], taking the place left vacant by the death of [[Edmund of Langley, 1st Duke of York]].<ref name=\"Cokayne 1959 546\"/>\n\nAccording to Tuck, Westmorland had little influence on the Scottish borders in the first years of Henry IV's reign, where the wardenships of the marches were monopolised by the Percys, leading to a growing rivalry between the two families. However, in 1403 the Percys, spurred on by various grievances, took up arms against the King, and suffered defeat at the [[Battle of Shrewsbury]] on 21 July 1403. [[Henry Percy, 1st Earl of Northumberland|Northumberland's]] son, Henry Percy (\"Hotspur\"), was slain at Shrewsbury, and Northumberland's brother, the [[Thomas Percy, 1st Earl of Worcester|Earl of Worcester]], was beheaded two days later. After Shrewsbury, King Henry ordered Westmorland to raise troops and prevent Northumberland's army, which was still in the north, from advancing south. On 6 August 1403,as a reward for his service in driving Northumberland back to [[Warkworth Castle]], Westmorland was granted the wardenship of the [[Scottish Marches|West March]] which Northumberland had held since 1399, the wardenship of the East March, formerly held by Hotspur, being granted to the King's 14-year-old son, [[John of Lancaster, 1st Duke of Bedford]].<ref name=\"Cokayne 1959 546\"/>\n\nTwo years later Northumberland, joined by [[Thomas Bardolf, 5th Baron Bardolf|Lord Bardolf]], again took up arms against the King. It had been Northumberland's plan to capture the earl by surprise at the outset, and in early May 1405, with 400 men, Northumberland made a surprise attack at the castle of [[Witton-le-Wear]], where he had been staying.  The attempt failed, as Westmorland had already fled. The earl speedily gathered an army, defeated a force of Percy allies at [[Topcliffe, North Yorkshire|Topcliffe]], and then marched towards York with Henry IV's son, [[John of Lancaster, 1st Duke of Bedford|John of Lancaster]], to confront a force of some 8000 men gathered on [[Shipton, North Yorkshire|Shipton]] Moor under the leadership of [[Richard Scrope (cleric)|Archbishop Richard Scrope]], [[Thomas de Mowbray, 4th Earl of Norfolk]], and Scrope's nephew, Sir William Plumpton. Outnumbered by Scrope's forces, Westmorland resorted to trickery,<ref>According to contemporary writers, Westmorland tricked Scrope into surrendering; however the later [[Thomas of Otterbourne|Otterbourne]] chronicler states that Scrope and his allies surrendered voluntarily (see Tait, 1894, p. 277).</ref> and led Scrope and his allies to believe that their demands would be accepted and their personal safety guaranteed. Once Scrope's army had been disbanded on 29 May, Scrope, Mowbray and Plumpton were arrested, summarily condemned to death for treason, and beheaded outside the walls of York on 8 June 1405. Although Westmorland handed Scrope and his allies over to the King at [[Pontefract Castle|Pontefract]], he played no role in their hasty and irregular trial and execution, having been sent north by the King on 4 June to seize Northumberland's castles. It is unclear whether Northumberland had initially planned to rebel openly in concert with Scrope, but in the event he gave Scrope no support, and fled to Scotland after his failed attempt to capture Westmorland. His estates were subsequently forfeited to the crown, and Ralph, earl of Westmorland, as a reward for his quelling of the 1405 rebellion without significant bloodshed, received a large grant of former Percy lands in [[Cumberland]] and [[Northumberland]] in June 1405.<ref>{{Harvnb|Cokayne|1959|p=546}}; {{Harvnb|Tait|1894|p=277}}; {{Harvnb|Tuck|2009}}.</ref>\n\nAfter the death of Henry IV Westmorland was mainly engaged in the defence of the northern border in his capacity as [[Warden of the Marches|Warden of the West March]] (1403\u20131414). In 1415 he decisively defeated an invading Scottish army at the [[Battle of Yeavering]].{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=552}} Westmorland played no part in [[Henry V of England|King Henry V's]] French campaigns, and Tuck notes that his relationship with Henry V was not close, perhaps partly because of the involvement of Westmorland's son-in-law, [[Thomas Grey (1384-1415)|Sir Thomas Grey]] of Heaton, in the [[Southampton Plot]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Tuck|2009}}.</ref> After Henry V's death, Westmorland was a member of the [[Regency (government)|Council of Regency]] during the minority of [[Henry VI of England|King Henry VI]].<ref name=\"Tait 1894 278\">{{Harvnb|Tait|1894|p=278}}.</ref>\n\nAccording to Tait, Westmorland was \"no inconsiderable builder\", citing his rebuilding of [[Sheriff Hutton Castle]] on a scale so magnificent that [[John Leland (antiquary)|Leland]] saw \"no house in the north so like a princely lodging\", his doubling of the entrance gateway of [[Raby Castle]] and the corresponding tower, and possibly his responsibility for the \"tall and striking tower\" of Richmond parish church. On 1 November 1410 Westmorland was granted licence to found a college for a master, six clerks, six \"decayed gentlemen\" and others at [[Staindrop]], towards the completion of which he left a bequest in his will.<ref name=\"Tait 1894 278\"/> He was probably responsible for the building of [[Penrith castle]] in Cumberland c.&nbsp;1412\u201313.<ref>Perriam, D.R., 'William Strickland's Tower in Penrith: Penrith Castle or Hutton Hall?' ''The English Heritage Historical Review'', vol.3 no.1 (1 June 2008), p.41</ref>\n\n==Marriages and issue==\n[[File:Ralph Neville, 1st Earl of Westmorland.png|thumb|200px|Contemporary miniature of the Earl of Westmorland with twelve of his children. A second miniature (not pictured) features his second wife, Lady Joan, with the rest of his children.]]\n[[File:Ralph and his wifes.jpg|thumb|200px|Effigy of Ralph Neville, 1st Earl of Westmorland and his two wives, [[Staindrop]] Church]]\n[[File:Richard Neville.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Ralph Neville's grandson Richard Neville aka \"The Kingmaker\"]]\nNeville consolidated the strength of his family by marriage alliances.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=552}} He married firstly [[Margaret de Stafford|Margaret Stafford]] (died 9 June 1396), the eldest daughter of [[Hugh de Stafford, 2nd Earl of Stafford|Hugh Stafford, 2nd Earl of Stafford]], and [[Philippa de Beauchamp|Philippa Beauchamp]], the daughter of [[Thomas de Beauchamp, 11th Earl of Warwick|Thomas Beauchamp, 11th Earl of Warwick]], by [[Katherine Mortimer, Countess of Warwick|Katherine Mortimer]], the daughter of [[Roger de Mortimer, 1st Earl of March|Roger Mortimer, 1st Earl of March]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Cokayne|1959|p=547}}; {{Harvnb|Richardson III|2011|p=246}}; {{Harvnb|Richardson IV|2011|p=74}}.</ref> They had two sons and six daughters:\n\n*Sir [[John Neville (d.1420)|John Neville]] (c. 1387{{snd}}before 20 May 1420), who married Elizabeth Holland, fifth daughter of [[Thomas Holland, 2nd Earl of Kent]], and [[Alice Holland, Countess of Kent|Alice FitzAlan]], and by her had three sons, [[Ralph Neville, 2nd Earl of Westmorland]], [[John Neville, Baron Neville]], and Sir Thomas Neville (before 20 May 1420{{snd}}1459), and a daughter, Margaret Neville (c. 1408{{snd}}before 1434).<ref name=\"Richardson III 2011 249\">{{Harvnb|Richardson III|2011|p=249}}.</ref>\n*Sir Ralph Neville (died 25 Feb 1458), who married, before 1411, his stepsister, Mary Ferrers, daughter of [[Robert Ferrers (1373-1396)|Robert Ferrers, 2nd Baron Ferrers]], and [[Joan Beaufort, Countess of Westmorland|Joan Beaufort]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Richardson II|2011|p=244}}; {{Harvnb|Richardson IV|2011|p=313}}.</ref>\n*Maud Neville (died October 1438), who married Peter Mauley, 5th [[Baron Mauley]].<ref name=\"Richardson III 2011 249\"/>\n*Alice Neville, who married firstly [[Thomas Grey (1384&ndash;1415)|Sir Thomas Grey]], beheaded 2 August 1415 for his part in the [[Southampton Plot]], and secondly Sir Gilbert Lancaster.<ref>{{Harvnb|Richardson II|2011|p=257}}.</ref>\n*[[Philippa de Neville|Philippa Neville]], who married, before 20 July 1399, [[Thomas Dacre, 6th Baron Dacre]] of Gilsland (died 5 January 1458).<ref>{{Harvnb|Cokayne|1916|p=18}}; {{Harvnb|Richardson II|2011|p=16}}.</ref>\n*Elizabeth Neville, who became a nun.\n*Anne Neville (born c. 1384), who married, before 3 February 1413, [[Umfraville|Sir Gilbert Umfraville]], son of Sir Thomas Umfreville (died 12 February 1391) and Agnes Grey (died 25 October 1420), daughter of [[Thomas Grey (chronicler)|Sir Thomas Grey of Heaton]] (d. before 22 October 1369). He was slain at the [[Battle of Baug\u00e9]] in Anjou on 22 March 1421.<ref>{{Harvnb|Richardson III|2011|pp=118\u201319}}.</ref>\n*Margaret Neville (died 1463/4), who married firstly, before 31 December 1413, [[Richard Scrope, 3rd Baron Scrope of Bolton]], and secondly, William Cressener, esquire.<ref>{{Harvnb|Richardson IV|2011|p=198}}.</ref>\n\nNeville married secondly, before 29 November 1396, at Ch\u00e2teau de Beaufort, Maine-et-Loire, Anjou, [[Joan Beaufort, Countess of Westmorland|Joan Beaufort]], the widow of [[Robert Ferrers (1373-1396)|Robert Ferrers, 2nd Baron Ferrers]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Richardson IV|2011|p=313}}; {{Harvnb|Weir|1999|p=108}}.</ref> Joan was the legitimated daughter of [[John of Gaunt, 1st Duke of Lancaster]], by his mistress and later third wife, [[Katherine Swynford]]. They had nine sons and five daughters:<ref>{{Harvnb|Richardson III|2011|p=246}}.</ref>\n\n*Joan Neville (c. 1398{{snd}}1453), who became a nun.\n*[[Eleanor Percy, Countess of Northumberland|Eleanor Neville]] (1398\u20131472), married firstly to [[Richard le Despencer, 4th Baron Burghersh]], secondly to [[Henry Percy, 2nd Earl of Northumberland]].\n*[[Katherine Neville, Duchess of Norfolk|Katherine Neville]] (c. 1399{{snd}}c. 1483), married firstly, on 12 January 1411 to [[John de Mowbray, 2nd Duke of Norfolk]], secondly to Sir Thomas Strangways, thirdly to John Beaumont, 1st Viscount Beaumont, fourthly to Sir [[John Woodville]] (died 12 August 1469).\n*[[Richard Neville, 5th Earl of Salisbury]] (1400\u20131460), married [[Alice Montacute, 5th Countess of Salisbury]]. Their son was [[Richard Neville, 16th Earl of Warwick]] (1428\u20131471), \"The Kingmaker\".\n*Henry Neville (c. 1400).\n*Thomas Neville (c. 1401).\n*Cuthbert Neville (c. 1402).\n*[[Robert Neville (bishop)|Robert Neville]] (1404\u20131457), Bishop of [[Bishop of Salisbury|Salisbury]] and [[Bishop of Durham|Durham]].\n*[[William Neville, 1st Earl of Kent]] (c. 1405\u22121463).\n*[[George Neville, 1st Baron Latimer]] (c. 1407\u22121469).\n*[[Anne Stafford, Duchess of Buckingham|Anne Neville]] (1414?\u20131480), married firstly to [[Humphrey Stafford, 1st Duke of Buckingham]], secondly to [[Walter Blount, 1st Baron Mountjoy]].\n*John Neville (c. 1411).\n*[[Edward Neville, 3rd Baron Bergavenny]] (c. 1414\u22121476).\n*[[Cecily Neville, Duchess of York|Cecily Neville]] (1415\u20131495), married to [[Richard, 3rd Duke of York]]. She was the mother of [[Edward IV of England|King Edward IV]] and [[Richard III of England|King Richard III]].\n[[File:Cecily neville.jpg|thumb|left|Cecily Neville]]\n\n==Death==\n{{multiple image\n| align = right\n| image1 = Wife2.jpg\n| width1 = 150\n| alt1 = \n| caption1 = \n| image2 = Wife1.jpg\n| width2 = 150\n| alt2 = \n| caption2 = \n| footer = The two wives of Ralph Neville, 1st Earl of Westmorland, from his monumental effigy, Staindrop Church. His first wife, left, on his right-hand side\n}}\nWestmorland died on 21 October 1425. He was buried in the choir of his collegiate church of St. Mary at Staindrop. The magnificent alabaster tomb with effigies of himself and his two wives there has been termed the finest sepulchral monument in the north of England.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=552}} Neither of his wives is buried with him.  His first wife, Margaret Stafford, was buried at [[Brancepeth]], [[County Durham|Durham]], while his second wife, Joan Beaufort, was buried with her mother under a carved stone canopy in the sanctuary of [[Lincoln Cathedral]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Cokayne|1959|p=547}}; {{Harvnb|Richardson III|2011|pp=246\u20137}}; {{Harvnb|Weir|1999|p=109}}.</ref>\n\nWestmorland was predeceased by his eldest son, Sir John Neville, and was succeeded in the title by his grandson, [[Ralph Neville, 2nd Earl of Westmorland]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Cokayne|1959|p=549}}.</ref>\n\n==Shakespeare and Westmorland==\nWestmorland is portrayed in [[William Shakespeare|Shakespeare's]] ''[[Henry IV, Part 1]]'',  ''[[Henry IV, Part 2]]'', and ''[[Henry V (play)|Henry V]]''.\n\nIn the opening scene of ''[[Henry IV, Part 1]]'', Westmorland is presented historically as an ally of [[Henry IV of England|King Henry IV]] against the Percys, and in the final scenes of the play as being dispatched to the north of England by the King after the [[Battle of Shrewsbury]] to intercept the [[Henry Percy, 1st Earl of Northumberland|Earl of Northumberland]].{{sfn|Tuck|2008}}\n\nIn Act IV of ''[[Henry IV, Part 2]]'', Westmorland is portrayed historically as having been principally responsible for quelling the Percy rebellion in 1405 by [[Richard Scrope (cleric)|Archbishop Scrope]] almost without bloodshed by successfully parleying with the rebels on 29 May 1405 at [[Shipton, North Yorkshire|Shipton]] Moor.{{sfn|Tuck|2008}}\n\nHowever, in ''[[Henry V (play)|Henry V]]'' Westmorland is unhistorically alleged to have resisted the arguments made in favour of war with France by [[Henry Chichele|Archbishop Chichele]] in the Parliament which began at [[Leicester]] on 30 April 1414. Following [[Hall's Chronicle|Hall]] and [[Holinshed's Chronicles|Holinshed]], Shakespeare attributes these arguments to Chichele<ref>{{Harvnb|Nicoll|1927|pp=71\u20134}}.</ref> at a time when Chichele was not yet formally Archbishop, although he had been appointed by the King immediately following the death of [[Thomas Arundel|Archbishop Arundel]] on 14 February 1414. Moreover, it is said that the Parliamentary rolls do not record Chichele's presence, and according to Tait the question of war with France was not discussed. In addition, Westmorland's speech urging the advantages of war against Scotland rather than France is said to be adapted from a work by the Scottish historian, [[John Major (philosopher)|John Major]], who was not born until half a century after the 1414 Parliament.<ref name=\"Tait 1894 278\"/>\n\nThe [[First Folio]] text of ''[[Henry V (play)|Henry V]]'' also unhistorically gives these lines to Westmorland on the eve of [[Battle of Agincourt|Agincourt]]:\n\n''O that we now had here''<br>\n''But one ten thousand of those men in England''<br>\n''That do no work today.'' (Henry V, IV.iii)\n\nWestmorland was not with [[Henry V of England|King Henry V]] on the 1415 campaign in France. On 17 April 1415 he was appointed to the [[Regency (government)|Council of Regency]] which was to govern England under the King's brother, [[John of Lancaster, 1st Duke of Bedford]], during the King's absence in France, with special responsibility for the [[Scottish Marches]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Cokayne|1959|p=546}}; {{Harvnb|Tuck|2008}}.</ref> In the first [[quarto]] text of the play, the foregoing lines are assigned to the [[Richard de Beauchamp, 13th Earl of Warwick|Earl of Warwick]].{{sfn|Tuck|2008}}\n\nIt has been claimed by Brenda James and Professor [[William Rubinstein]] that Neville's great-great-great-grandson [[Henry Neville (politician)|Sir Henry Neville]] wrote the works of [[Shakespearean authorship|William Shakespeare]].\n\n==Ancestry==\n{{unreferenced section|date=March 2014}}\n{{ahnentafel\n|collapsed=yes |align=center\n|boxstyle_1=background-color: #fcc;\n|boxstyle_2=background-color: #fb9;\n|boxstyle_3=background-color: #ffc;